76561197969039327,Recommended,211900,9355212,"Posted: 5 March, 2014",all,EddyVegas,"Sid Meier said that good games are a series of interesting choices. This game fits that bill, in spades.The genius of this game is that the interesting choices start on Turn 1 of this turn based strategy game, and they never let up. There is no down time. Do you go for that coal mine, even though that will leave you far from your home base? Do you even have an army that can win, if you do decide to attack? Should you wait a couple turns to summon more creatures, even though you really, really, really need that gold? Did you leave enough defenders at your home base? Shold I save up my Druid herbs to upgrade my apprentice, or should I spend them now to better go on the offensive? The interesting choices never stop, all through the game.However...If you just fire it up and click Start New Game, you won't know how to do anything, you'll think the game is stupid, the graphics are ugly, the UI is unintuitive (actually, this part is kinda true) and never play it again. This happened to me, in fact. This is an old fashioned game. You gotta use the manual, I won't say read the manual, but use it. Leave it open while you play and Alt-Tab. If the game clicks for you, after a game or two you will be dying to read the manual all the way through. But it's gonna take a bit of work at the beginning because of the wonky UI. I think your effort will be richly rewarded.This game is easily worth full price, and if you can catch it on sale, it's the steal of the century."
